After 5 amazing years, Angus @fortyounces and I have decided to move on from owning White Oak Tattoo. It is with great pleasure and excitement to announce that we have officially sold White Oak to our dear friends and long time artist Matt Beirne and his wife Heather who has worked closely with us since the beginning 🖤🖤

We built White Oak to last and we couldn’t be prouder of what it is today. It is an incredibly beautiful studio with amazing artists and guests. Matt and Heather are some of our favorite people and we can’t think of anyone else we’d rather pass the torch to. @mattbtattoos @hbeirne22 

As other opportunities arise in both business, and our personal lives, unfortunately we have to pick and choose where our efforts are spent. After many years of love and care, and with a lot of life changes post-pandemic, we have decided the best thing for us and White Oak is to allow it to grow with the absolute best new guardians.

I will continue to tattoo at White Oak, while also spending time working in NYC with Inked, @inked_nyc @inked_magzine_ and continuing my usual travel with my sponsors. @cheyenne_tattooequipment @eternalink 

We have some exciting prospects on the horizon that we’ve been working towards for the last few years, and can’t wait to share them in due time. This allows us to build something new and focus on side projects while giving my clients the attention their tattoos deserve. I’m excited to pour absolutely everything I can creatively into my tattoo projects this year. 

It has been an incredible ride and we cannot wait to watch White Oak continue to thrive and grow. 

Please stay tuned for new adventures and thank you to everyone who continues to love and support this studio and it’s inhabitants. 

So much love

Gia and Angus

I did the Ai “recreation of yourself in different eras” thingy for fun! And boy did it open a can of wormy worms 🪱 quite unexpectedly. 

I didn’t use Lensa which has all this controversy around it (run by humans btw) and when I did this I was unaware of these upsets. I used a heritage site. 

However, a lot of people are upset about Ai making art and don’t understand why I as an artist myself am not also upset.

I stand pretty neutral at this moment about Ai. 
Is it questionable as art? Yes. Is it worthy of debate? Absolutely. 
That being said, my neutrality is because we don’t create in a vacuum and we need to be careful when defining “morality or ethics” in “art” because you risk becoming a hypocrite if you follow your own evolution as an artist back far enough. 

Humans have taken, borrowed, repurposed, remade, stolen and recreated from each other and the world in art, design, invention and fashion forever. So Ai doing the same thing is ironically very human. 

For me, there isn’t enough info yet. The fears and debates around the integrity of Ai is not new, it has clouded both photography, and digital artists for decades.
Ai is just the newest upset. 
If this bothers you, would you feel differently if you were the artist requesting Ai to create using your ideas? If it was a tool? 
In art school I took a class on this debate and how we potentially would never be artists without it. If a photographer takes a photograph of a statue a sculptor made, and sells it for profit who owns the “art”? Because one became something else. If a photorealist tattooer makes an EXACT replica as a tattoo of a person, painting or photo? Hyperrealist artists copy exact photographs with skill but is it theirs? And for the love of all that’s holy, who actually decides? 

One could argue that’s how we evolved to where we are as artists today. The questionable integrity of “art” is deeply rooted in all art history. It even adds value in art to a lot of degrees. Artists have always had shadowy creations. The most innovation in art have always been moments of breaking all the “rules” 

Thank you for all your comments of love and hate below ❤️ I value them all because that’s learning!

Hi! Sooooo some of y’all may not have been following me for a long time, so I figured I’d introduce myself. I speak very openly about things I feel are important. I’m not a creator of content, never have been and never will be. I’m not just a tattoo artist but I am a cancer survivor, an assault survivor, a homelessness survivor and I stand up for and fight for all people to have the right to live a life of liberty and freedom in the pursuit of happiness. That means I have strong opinions. I stand up for marginalized people and I subscribe to most intersectional feminist views. I have high ideals of manners, morality and ethics. I also believe in attaining alignment through love, peace and acceptance of all multifaceted aspects of ourselves. I hold space for others and I will always use my voice. I also have a quirky and dark sense of humor and don’t take myself all that seriously lol because if we can’t laugh at our own mistakes how do we ever survive? Lol 😂 I am an artist yes, I love aesthetic, beauty, soul growth, the cosmos and thinking deeply. I love romantic things, and that includes speaking openly, questioning strongly and having empathy. I believe self awareness is the key to joy and a good life no matter your struggles. But I will ALWAYS choose my integrity over clout. So if you’re just here for tattoos and don’t care to nor are interested in my humanity, and it bothers you, you can unfollow me! because quality in my community over quantity or hiding who I am, is well, a core value. Personally I don’t like echo chambers, I like diversity. I do keep most of my opinions on TikTok.. however, this is me! Thank you for following me if you stick around! I adore you. ♥️♥️♥️♥️

To see this iconic woman on the cover of @vogue Beauty” issue is heartwarming and exhilarating for many reasons. I haven’t read the article yet, waiting on my issue. Beauty is such a vast and powerful force in all its many many forms and concepts. It is what inspires us, not just in looks or the value of “skin deep” but it is at its core what we as all people are profoundly moved by, whether it’s music or art or sculpture or a person, or especially nature and life it’s self. It’s what gives us awe. But I’ve had a lot of conversations of the years about tattooing being the oldest form of human expression alongside jewelry. It’s an expression of life in all our forms. It’s an act like makeup or fashion that can have deep culture significance or personal meaning and expression. It is owned by no one and all of humanity and everyone at the same time. I’ve been tattooing for 20 years, and to see it evolve and grow from tiny insular communities of tattoo shops to cultures holding onto their traditions against all odds to the fanning of the flames of such a deeply human thing catch like wildfire across all peoples and places, across all ages, genders and stations in life has been the most beautiful thing to witness and be a part of. Today we have the very first research driven archeological book ever published on tattooing “Ancient Ink” and Tattoo artists are pushing the boundaries of fine art in skin. The idea that tattooing is permanent yet it’s only along for the ride with us in our skin has a magical self possession unmatched by any other form of expression. To have a tattoo is such a personal thing. A visual language. Something that cannot be possessed nor handed down to any other. Grateful to be here. ♥️

40 has been so unexplainable. I have had more grief in one year than most of my life. Loss of my dog of 14 years, the sudden loss of my baby brother, two cancer scares. One major surgery, selling my studio, moving to NYC. Reconnecting with my sisters on spiritual levels, rediscovering myself as more than an artist, redefining connections and intimacy. Cutting through the noise. Starting over again in major ways. They say grief isn’t a feeling, it’s an experience. Something that has no finite end. You get these things called SUGS, “sudden upwelling of grief” where you are randomly washed in the feelings of it. I feel like I have made so many good choices despite it all and I genuinely believe it’s because I allow my body and my life to remain open and yielding. I’ve grown more in one year than I have in decades. My life has always been one of uproot. Travel, movement and constant walking back and forth in all aspects to attain balance and peace in all the storms. But the greatest lesson I’ve learned in my year of grief or my year of magical thinking is that when we give up control, we allow things to be just as they are, and we listen to our bodies and our intuition, there is always a light. There’s a great quote that says “keep a small fire burning, no matter how small, how hidden” that has been my mantra. That has seen me through. We are incredibly resilient when we let go of expectations, “should and would and could” the unfurling of every moment just as is. When my brother Brae, passed away, he gave me a gift. From that day I’ve woken up at 5am every morning. I sit in contemplation and tell myself to let everything be. In doing this, I can hear myself, my intuition, the divine spark we all have. So even in my grief there is so much love and joy.

I’ve been 
Reflecting on my 20 year tattoo career. 
Mistakes I’ve made, leaps of change and growth I’ve made. How close the tattoo industry is, and these micro moments of momentous change that pushes us as artists forward or holds us back. From tv shows, to social media to technological advances to transparency. I’ve witnessed our industry go from small insular communities to a global phenomenon. I’ve been apprentice, artist, studio owner, mentor. I’ve been liked and disliked. I’ve been friend and foe. 
I’ve been everything a human can be. But I’ve grown so much, I grew up as a human while I was growing up as a tattooer. I started at 21. I’m now almost 41. A 20 year career that I literally grew up in. I’ve witnessed the worst, I’ve experienced the worst. I’ve witnessed the most beautiful and been a part of the most beautiful. I can genuinely say I have a rich history of wild experiences and humbling experiences. But throughout it all, what I’ve come to now, at this moment, is that we as artists, clients, collectors, studio owners and fans are, is a human community that encompasses the vast experience of just being alive in this world. To tattoo and be tattooed is so human. Creating for each other the best we can. I think we forget to take a moment and look at the awe that is to be a tattooer. To be able to work so closely and intimately with each other and clients. For better or worse, this is our home. Our life. Tattooing is owned by nobody and everybody. I’m grateful to be here. The good, the bad, the profound. There has been nothing more character building, more humbling. I just wanted to take a moment and thank all of my followers who have supported me through the years, on my personal and professional journey. 
Tattooing is such a unique thing, I feel grateful for it. Every day. Even the hard days. I think you have to have a certain amount of grit, unrelenting passion, self awareness, willingness to grow and empathy to be a creator, an artist of any ilk, a good tattooer. A few things I am so thankful to have earned ❤️

Key take aways: Instagram’s algorithm 
Is “niching down”
This means only 10% of your followers will see your content. 
It’s meant to rebuild your community… 
So in a way you can go back to personal/professional 
Posts for true engagement. 
However, my take away is to just live your life. Post what you want, when you want and how you want, because it doesn’t really matter anymore.
This whole social media/ tech algorithm thing we have all been prisoner to in some way since FB took over, reminds me of a great book “Einstein’s Dreams” where all his theories are each put into the form of a dream. One story talks about how people discovered the further they were from earths gravity, the slower they aged, the slower time moved. So people built tall houses and the richer, the taller, until they lived their whole existence alone in towers away from the world. But some, some decided to cast off this absurdity and embrace aging and time and lived their lives on the earth with each other in community, connection, love and laughter… which would you choose? Personally I’m relieved to give up on the code breaking of social media participation and the reality that you can’t to any degree and still have a life. The returning to trusting your community will find you, and you them is such a freeing experience. So post what you want, how you want, when you want. Let’s live on the earth together. It’s better down here 🥰

I’ve lived an incredible life. From homelessness to riding freight trains for years, shed living, boat living, farm living, mountain living, desert exploring and tattooing around the world, beating cancer, creating and building a life with my own two hands, a lot of luck, a lot of mentors and all around magical communities and incredible friends who are some of the most creative people I’ve ever met, who keep me grounded, inspired and motivated to continue to grow. It’s been rough and it’s been beautiful. Last year was my year of grief, I lost my baby brother to a debilitating mental illness and my entire world shifted. I started doing shadow work. Learning to integrate the things inside us we think are ugly, we don’t want to face, we are told we must reject, has been more healing and more freeing than I can express. I’ve learned there is no such thing as continual happiness or perfection, only moments. That the dark times are just as essential as the light. When we learn to accept and make space for these in ourselves and others, it’s a wholeness. Something that you never lose. Shout out to all my shadow workers out there who have helped guide me, inspire me, teach me to love myself and the journey. I love you all 🖤🤍 ☯️ as someone once said “be kind to each other, we are all survivors”

Well, the universe sometimes has other plans for us. I was on a journey to find home. To be closer to family. I don’t know if this project is beyond my means but I’m going to take the first step and hopefully this is the first post of many on this new journey. I am planning now to be relocating to the Scranton Pennsylvania area to continue the restoration on this old church into a tattoo studio and seminar/learning sanctuary. The possibilities would actually FREE me to be with my family as much as I want and need while also creating something needed in the tattoo world. A retreat space for established artists. A place to tattoo that is learning, community building and inspiration. Not a shop really but something more. I’m not sure how it will play out but I am incredibly excited about this. Which means, I’ll be tattooing in Pennsylvania again!! NYC and travel appointments currently on the books are good! While I suss out the scope and availability, I’m taking all new projects in PA Scranton, until I either collapse in on myself or manage to wrangle this beautiful beast into something holy. Easy to get too, beautiful area and in a church. I came to NYC to clear my head and give the city a go. But as much as I love my community here and the city, it’s not for me. I need more wild and more to build, more purpose to thrive. And if you happen to be a restoration specialist, construction anything, remodeler, wood worker, tile expert, designer or anything Helpful and want to pitch in for big big tattoo trade? Or an artist who wants to join in this space collaboratively? Come at me! The energy here is peaceful, the basement only slightly creepy. I may need a witch or two lol. Here’s to 2024 💕🩷
